description:
## Severity
Major
## Dimension
concurrency
## Location
src/tools/bash/mod.rs:117-152
## Violation
`finished` is set to `true` from TWO independent threads — the stdout reader (line 124) and the wait thread (line 150). The stdout reader sets `finished=true` on stdout EOF, which can fire BEFORE `child.wait()` reaps the child and populates `exit_status`. Consumers observe `is_running=false` with `exit_code=None` — an impossible state per the public contract.

Quoted source (mod.rs:117-152):
```
            thread::spawn(move || {
                let reader = BufReader::new(stdout);
                for line in reader.lines().map_while(Result::ok) {
                    if let Ok(mut buf) = buffer.lock() {
                        buf.push(line);
                    }
                }
                finished_clone.store(true, Ordering::SeqCst);
            });
...
        thread::spawn(move || {
            if let Ok(status) = child_for_wait.wait() {
                if let Ok(mut es) = exit_status_clone.lock() {
                    *es = status.code();
                }
                finished_clone.store(true, Ordering::SeqCst);
            }
        });
```

The test `b3_get_output_finished_shell_is_running_false` already hides this race with a 400ms sleep.
## Mandated refactor
1. Remove the `finished.store(true)` from the stdout reader; only the wait thread is authoritative for process lifecycle.
2. Introduce separate flags: `stdout_closed`, `stderr_closed`, `reaped` if any consumer truly cares about stream EOF.
3. Make `get_output` only return `is_running=false` after the wait thread has populated `exit_status`, so the (is_running=false, exit_code=None) state cannot be observed.
